go&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Chicago&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-226-68295-2&amp;rft.aulast=Principe&amp;rft.aufirst=Lawrence&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dcs9_mXyN0OsC%26lpg%3DPP1%26dq%3Dlawrence%2520principe%2520secrets%26pg%3DPP1%23v%3Donepage%26q%3Dlawrence%2520principe%2520secrets%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJabir+ibn+Hayyan" class="Z3988" about="#mwt33" id="mwAgQ"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt33" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAgU"/>, « Jabir Ibn Haiyan, known by the name of the alchemist Geber of the Middle Ages, is generally known as the Father of Chemistry »</span></li><li about="#cite_note-14" id="cite_note-14"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-14" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-14" class="mw-reference-text">Paul Kraus "Dignitaires de la hierarchie religieuse selon Gabir ibn Hayyan', Bulletin de l'Institut Francais d'Archeologie Orientale de Caire (1942): 85.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-15" id="cite_note-15"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-15" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-15" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt60" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"title":{"wt":"Imamology in Ismaili Gnosis"},"last":{"wt":"Diana"},"first":{"wt":"Steigerwald"},"publisher":{"wt":"Manohar Publishers &amp; Distributors"},"year":{"wt":"2015"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-93-5098-081-1"},"location":{"wt":"New Delhi"},"page":{"wt":"141"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAgY">Diana, Steigerwald (2015). <i id="mwAgc">Imamology in Ismaili Gnosis</i>. New Delhi: Manohar Publishers &amp; Distributors. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAgg"> </span>141. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwAgk">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAgo"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-93-5098-081-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-93-5098-081-1" id="mwAgs">978-93-5098-081-1</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Imamology+in+Ismaili+Gnosis&amp;rft.place=New+Delhi&amp;rft.pages=141&amp;rft.pub=Manohar+Publishers+%26+Distributors&amp;rft.date=2015&amp;rft.isbn=978-93-5098-081-1&amp;rft.aulast=Diana&amp;rft.aufirst=Steigerwald&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJabir+ibn+Hayyan" class="Z3988" about="#mwt60" id="mwAgw"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt60" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAg0"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-Nasr-16" id="cite_note-Nasr-16"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Nasr_16-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Nasr_16-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Nasr_16-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Nasr-16" class="mw-reference-text">S.N. Nasr, "Life Sciences, Alchemy and Medicine", The Cambridge History of Iran, Cambridge, Volume 4, 1975, p. 412: "Jabir is entitled in the traditional sources as al-Azdi, al-Kufi, al-Tusi, al-Sufi. There is a debate as to whether he was an Arab from Kufa who lived in Khurasan, or a Persian from Khorasan who later went to Kufa or whether he was, as some have suggested, of Syrian origin and later lived in Persia and Iraq".</span></li><li about="#cite_note-17" id="cite_note-17"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-17" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-17" class="mw-reference-text">Selin, Helaine (2008). Encyclopaedia of the History of Science, Technology, and Medicine in Non-Western Cultures. Springer Science &amp; Business Media. p. 101."Elsewhere his name is given as Abu Musa, and he is variously described as Tusi, Tartusi or Tarsusi, Harranian and from Khorasan (Holmyard 1923: 47)."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-18" id="cite_note-18"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-18" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-18" class="mw-reference-text">Holmyard, Eric John, Introduction to The Works of Geber, translated by Richard Russell. (London: Dent, 1928), p. vii: "Abu Musa Jabir ibn Hayyan, generally known merely as Jabir, was the son of a druggist belonging to the famous South Arabian tribe of Al-Azd. Members of this tribe had settled at the town of Kufa, in Iraq, shortly after the Muhammadan conquest in the seventh century A.D., and it was in Kufa that Hayyan the druggist lived."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-19" id="cite_note-19"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-19" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-19" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt61" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/?id=Kl1COWj9ubAC&amp;pg=PA178&amp;lpg=PA178&amp;dq=jabir+ibn+hayyan+persian+alchemist#v=onepage&amp;q=jabir%20ibn%20hayyan%20persian%20alchemist&amp;f=false"},"title":{"wt":"Tradition, Transmission, Transformation: Proceedings of Two Conferences on Pre-Modern Science Held at the University of Oklahoma"},"last":{"wt":"Ragep"},"first":{"wt":"F. Jamil"},"last2":{"wt":"Ragep"},"fir