%2Balchemist%23v%3Donepage%26q%3Djabir%2520ibn%2520hayyan%2520persian%2520alchemist%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJabir+ibn+Hayyan" class="Z3988" about="#mwt61" id="mwAhY"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt61" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAhc"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-20" id="cite_note-20"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-20" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-20" class="mw-reference-text">George Sarton, Introduction to the History of Science, Pub. for the Carnegie Institution of Washington, by the Williams &amp; Wilkins Company, 1931, vol. 2 pt. 1, p. 1044: "Was Geber, as the name would imply, the Persian alchemist Jabir ibn Haiyan?"</span></li><li about="#cite_note-21" id="cite_note-21"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-21" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-21" class="mw-reference-text">William R. Newman, Gehennical Fire: The Lives of George Starkey, an American Alchemist in the Scientific Revolution, Harvard University Press, 1994. p. 94: "According to traditional bio-bibliography of Muslims, Jabir ibn Hayyan was a Persian alchemist who lived at some time in the eighth century and wrote a wealth of books on virtually every aspect of natural philosophy."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-22" id="cite_note-22"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-22" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-22" class="mw-reference-text">Cyril Glassé; Huston Smith, <i id="mwAhg">The New Encyclopedia of Islam</i>, (2003), Rowman Altamira, p. 233: "Jabir ibn Hayyan. A celebrated alchemist, not a Muslim, but a Harranian from the community of the Harranian "Sabians" of North Syria."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-Holmyard1931-23" id="cite_note-Holmyard1931-23"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Holmyard1931_23-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Holmyard1931_23-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Holmyard1931_23-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-Holmyard1931_23-3"><span class="mw-linkback-text">4 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Holmyard1931-23" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt62" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Holmyard"},"first":{"wt":"Eric John"},"title":{"wt":"Makers of Chemistry"},"url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/?id=NZcaAAAAIAAJ"},"year":{"wt":"1931"},"publisher":{"wt":"The Clarendon press"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAhk">Holmyard, Eric John (1931). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/?id=NZcaAAAAIAAJ" id="mwAho"><i id="mwAhs">Makers of Chemistry</i></a>. The Clarendon press.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Makers+of+Chemistry&amp;rft.pub=The+Clarendon+press&amp;rft.date=1931&amp;rft.aulast=Holmyard&amp;rft.aufirst=Eric+John&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DNZcaAAAAIAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJabir+ibn+Hayyan" class="Z3988" about="#mwt62" id="mwAhw"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt62" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAh0"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-24" id="cite_note-24"><a href="./Jabir_ibn_Hayyan#cite_ref-24" rel="mw:referencedBy